So, there it is. Neural networks can be said to learn like us if you consider the way they build hierarchies of features just like we do. But when you see the features themselves, they are nothing like what we would use. The networks give you almost no explanation for the features that they learn.
Neural networks are good function approximators. When we build and train one, we mostly just care about its accuracy â€” On what percentage of the test samples does it give positive results?
This works incredibly well for a lot of purposes because modern neural nets can have remarkably high accuracies â€” upward of 98% is not uncommon (meaning that the chances of failure are just 1 in a 100!)
